<DOC><DOCNO> AP881004-0036 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0154EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Durano     10-04 0260</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Obit-Durano,0269</SECOND><HEAD>Former Congressman Dies</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix slug.</NOTE><DATELINE>CEBU CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ramon Durano, a formercongressman, business leader and one of the country's most colorfulpoliticians, has died of cancer, his family announced. He was 82.   Durano, who died Monday, virtually owned Danao, a city of 60,000north of Cebu. Many Danao residents were born in Durano's hospital,worked in his factories, retired to his home for the elderly andwere buried in his cemetery.   Durano was born Dec. 24, 1905 to a prosperous Cebu family. Hewas elected to the House of Representatives from Cebu in 1949 andserved until President Ferdinand Marcos abolished the legislaturein 1972.   In January, Durano was elected mayor of Danao, defeating his sonThaddaeus in a bitter campaign.   Durano was a longtime rival of the Osmena family, Cebu's othermajor political dynasty. Election battles between the two clanswere often marked by violence and allegations of massivevote-buying on all sides.   In his autobiography, Durano described himself as a politicalrealist.   ``I must say that like a determined boxer in the ring, apolitician must know how to defend himself, know his opponent'sweak and strong points and slug it out as expected of him,'' Duranosaid.   During his term in Congress, Durano was involved in at leastfour fistfights with rivals on the House floor.   He remained a devoted follower of Marcos, describing him in hisautobiography as the greatest leader the Philippines ever produced.   He is survived by his wife Beatriz, three daughters and two sons.</TEXT></DOC>